[{"id":"VR813082","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a graph of a line in the first and fourth quadrants of a coordinate plane. The horizontal axis is labeled “t, in seconds,” and the numbers 5 through 20, increments of 5, are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled “phi sub B,” and the numbers negative 0.4 through 0.4, in increments of 0.2, are indicated. The line begins at 0.4 along the vertical axis and moves diagonally downward and to the right, intersects the horizontal axis at about 15 seconds, and ends at the point with approximate coordinates 20 comma negative 0.15.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR813082.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The graph shows the magnetic flux through a circular loop as a function of time. Which of the following claims about the induced current in the circular loop is correct and gives an appropriate justification?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR813082_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The induced current changes direction at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 15 seconds\"><math alttext=\"t equals 15 seconds\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></span></span>, because the flux changes sign at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 15 seconds\"><math alttext=\"t equals 15 seconds\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The induced current changes direction at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 15 seconds\"><math alttext=\"t equals 15 seconds\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mi mat